segments.text: This is May 19, I believe.
I have the pleasure of being at 1212 Orr Street, getting ready to chat with Mary Eccles.
Ms. Eccles, would you say a sentence or two, and let's see if your machine is picking up.
Well, I will.
I wanted to start out when my father came in August of 2009.
All right.
Are you interested in that?
Oh, yes, yes.
Tell, first of all, tell me about his background.
Where did he grow up and where did he?
Well, he grew up in Mississippi and he was at the University of, when he was at Mississippi A&M, he graduated and taught there.
And he came here in August of 09.
He came to me in the physics department.
which he was never in.
When he got here, they were organizing for the first time the electrical engineering department, which he took over and kept.
Had he majored in electrical engineering?
Yes.
How did he get recruited?
Who contacted him?
I have no idea about that.
How did he come?
On the train, I presume.
Oh, yeah, on the train.
And my mother was crippled.
And I don't know how she managed, but she did.
Because they had to walk up from the station down there to the houses.
And they had a house.
It was Throckmorton, but it really was quality rose, what they always called it.
What did they bring with them in the way of furniture or belongings?
I don't have any idea, but not a lot.
And my mother had taught in the little school on the campus at Mississippi A&M.
What did she teach?
The beginners.
Oh, elementary school?
Yeah, yeah.
And were there any children at that point?
No, and I came in January.
They came in August, and I arrived in January.
Where were you?
Were you born at home?
At home.
The doctor razor came out from Brian Ray horse and buggy razor raise RAZOR.
And so you you were born in the house on the campus, yeah.
Who was the president then?
You know, I've been thinking all morning about that, and I'm not sure.
I think that it was Milner.
Do you have any idea what your father's first salary was?
No.
But it wasn't very much.
None of them were very much.
How long did they live in that house?
Well, they lived in that house.
until 1918, and then they moved two houses up the street.
Describe that first house as you remember it.
Well, you know, it was just, it was just, it was home, and just a house.
How big was it?
Bedrooms?
We had about three or four bedrooms.
And to every house on campus, there was a maid's quarters.
They had maid's quarters.
Did y'all have a full-time maid?
Yep, we did.
And did she have a family or was she by herself?
She was by herself.
Describe the, how many,
How many faculty houses were there?
Do you remember?
How big was the neighborhood of faculty?
Well, on our street, they were, all the houses that were there except, they built one for later on when the, I'll tell you in a minute.
Dr. Thomas came.
They built him a house in there in between our old house.
By then we had moved up the street between our house and the one next to it.
I forgot who lived down below us, our house.
And then the Youngbloods, he was head of the
Well, isn't that awful?
We'll get it later.
Yeah, yeah.
Describe your neighbors.
Well, that was them, and then on the other side of us was Dr. Fraps, who was a state chemist.
Frap, F-R-A-P?
F-R-A-P-S, Fraps.
Mm-hmm.
And...
Dr. Ball lived right across the street from us.
B-A-L-L, Ball.
He was biology.
And next to him was Dean Pereira.
And as you know, Dean Pereira was the only one who owned his own home.
It was on campus, but it was his with the understanding, of course, that when he
gave it up, it went over to the university.
Was that P-U-R-Y-E-A-R?
P-U-R-Y-E-A-R.
He was the dean of the college.
Do you remember him by personality?
Definitely.
He was an old bachelor.
And he always weighed us.
He walked with a cane, and when we were real little, we were allowed to be picked.
You know, he'd pick us up on his cane and weighed us.
And who were some of your playmates as you were a youngster?
Okay.
All right.
Mary Frapps, who lived on the other side.
She was a little bit older, but she was there.
And Virginia Burns and Julia Ball, who lived across the street.
And then later, when the Waltons moved out on campus, they moved into the house that we originally lived in.
And they and Ethel and I were very close friends.
Describe Mr. Walton.
Well, you know, it's hard for me to do that because he was so special.
We just grew up, you know, and I spent as much time in their house as I did in my own home, and it was just my second home.
What made him special?
Well, just because he was there, I guess.
Did he have presents for little girls?
Oh, no, nothing like that.
No, nothing like that.
No, he had...
four children of his own.
What did he like to do?
Did he have any hobbies or things?
Not that I can remember.
We bought our milk from them.
They had a cow and we got our milk from them.
And so they had a cow on the campus and it was milked.
Oh yeah, oh yeah.
I think we had one originally because that wasn't good enough for me, anything wasn't good enough for me because I was that first little girl.
Where did y'all buy groceries?
They ordered them.
Each morning you called in to Brian to Mr.
I don't know what his name was in a minute, and ordered what you had to have for the day, and he brought it out in the afternoon, delivered it.
In a truck?
Well, a horse-drawn truck.
Oh, a wagon.
Yeah, yeah.
And was there any place out here near the college to buy groceries?
No place.
It was years and years before there was any place.
Go back as far as your memory can.
Describe what was on the campus.
What buildings were here?
The main building, which burned after, you know, and then was rebuilt.
All right.
It was here when you came, the main building that burned.
Also, as far as I know, the
the electrical engineering and the civil engineering buildings and there were dormitories and they went up that main drag just like they always did.
Was Sully's statue there?
Oh no, that came later.
Do you remember when the main building burned?
I was real small then, and I know it burned, but I... You don't remember seeing it or anything?

But when the floods came and when the river, Brazos River got out and washed everything away, we'd go up into the top floor, or up, I guess, on the roof of the administration building, and we could see what was going on over there.
Out to the west.
Yeah, yeah.
Do you remember when the main building was built?
Do you remember watching that happen?
No.
Where did you and your friends, where did y'all play?
In our yards.
And we always, at night, everybody got out and played until dark.
Just in the neighborhood.
Did the students ever come over to the faculty area?
No, except that they worked over there.
My father always had them in the yard.
That was his way of helping him get an education.
He paid him to do the yard work.
Doing yard work.
Yeah, yeah.
And in old school, we had to go to Bryan to school.
How did you get to Bryan?
Well, we walked down to Speza Hall and got on a streetcar, and sometimes we got there and sometimes we didn't, but then that's the way we went.
And that was until 1920.
Where, what school in Bryan, where was the building?
Do you remember?
Yeah, it was out this way.
It's still there, but it's changed a number of times, different names, so I don't have, but it was close to, well, Texas Avenue.
It was about three or four blocks from there.
You walk.
Was it that old elementary school over by the old St. Joseph Hospital?
over toward where the Astons lived?
It was in there someplace, yeah.
Do you remember who the teachers were, any of your?
Well, I used to, but I didn't stop.
Mother taught me until I was in the third grade, so I didn't have to go as soon as some of them did.
When you did go, about how many students went to school in Bryan from the college?
All of us.
But I mean we all just walked, the whole gang of us just walked to get on the streetcar and we rode in there.
And if an order came and we didn't have clothes enough, some one of the mothers, by then there were some cars on the camp, a few cars, and they would bring in our
jackets in for us.
Would you all fill up a streetcar when all the kids were on it?
Oh, I think so.
And so you went to school there.
Because it was all the way through high school.
You went to school there until 1920?
Let's back up.
How did World War I affect the campus?
Do you remember?
Yes.
My father had charge of the

the program for the the students that were i mean the the soldiers that were there it was were under him and he worked with the uh well fort sam who's and i remember the thing that impressed me as a little girl was that we had a a special telephone that of course we couldn't use but it went direct to the to the military
Now, were the students that he was helping, were these all A&M students, or had some young men been brought?
Oh, these were soldiers that were put there by the Army during World War I, just like they did during World War II.
And what was he teaching them?
Well, he didn't teach them.
He was just over the whole program.
Oh, I see.
Yeah.
I'm sure they had their own teachers because it was a military thing, but they were just stationed there during the war.
Now how close was it from your house to the dormitories where the students lived, the A&M students?
Well, it was about two blocks.
And when you all referred
If someone asked you where you lived, did you all say we live at college?
What did you call this community?
It was always College Station.
I don't know.
Or A&M Campus.
No, it was A&M Campus.
And when the war was over, did a bunch of veterans come back to school?
I don't know.
I expect they did.
They did it after World War II, but I think they probably did.
Right.
So you were in Bryan until 1920.
I was never in Bryan.
I mean, went to school.
Then you came back and went to school on the campus?
The school was across the street from our house.
On the campus.
On the campus.
Please describe the building as much as you can.
Well, it was a nice size building, a two-story building, and all of the school was there.
And the house, the Ball's house, they were these old houses.
They may be, you probably don't know about them, but then, I mean, they were the original buildings.
houses for the original university.
And they were across the street from us.
There were one, two, three, I think there were four or five.
And anyway, there were two stories.
And one of them, they made it into the teacherage, the one that was closest to the thing.
But also, some of our courses were taught by Indian professors.
Do you remember some of those teachers?
Well, I can't give you their names now.
But we took physics and chemistry and things like that
University professors.
And you graduated what year?
I graduated early and I graduated in 1926.
About how many were in your graduation class?
Oh, about, I graduated a year ahead.
There were about seven or eight of us.
What did y'all call the name of the school?
consolidated.
It was already consolidated because they brought them all in from all the neighboring areas.
What did did the what did y'all call the kids that lived out in the country?
I'm sure we were nice about it but they with our home economics

we would make money the time or two we'd sell peanut brittle and I can remember to this day how horrible it was because they got on their buses and went home at four o'clock and we had to wash all those.
All those peanuts?
Those pans and they were horrible.
And as you were in high school, who were your closest friends?
Ethel.
Walton and Mary Frapps and Julia Ball.
We were all, you know, right there in the neighborhood.
When you were in high school, was it acceptable to have a date with an Aggie student?
In fact, I went to some of the dances when I was 12 because they needed girls so badly.
Please describe those dances.
What were they like?
Where were they held?
Well, they were held in Speza Hall.
And the faculty wives chaperoned.
They were all there and chaperoned them.
And when I got into college and came home, then at midnight,
Of course, there's no place to go to get a bite to eat or anything, so we always went to our houses.
They took turns.
One would have it one time, and we'd walk down, military walking, to the house and have our refreshments and then go back to the dance.
Now, Guyon Hall was there.
Well, it wasn't in the beginning, but it was later.
Okay, so that Sabisa was at the other end, and the academic building was there by the time you were in high school.
It had been rebuilt.
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
At a dance at Sabisa, what did you young ladies wear?
Oh, long dresses.
And for the RVs, ballroom things, we had to have four.
Because they were Thursday night, Friday night, and Saturday night.
Which one?
That was for the RVs.
Which dance was most important?
Well, the RVs had theirs in the spring.
Then there was a big one at Thanksgiving and a big final ball.
But they were, also we had dances on the weekends.
And did, there was no problem about dancing?
No Baptist complained about?
Well, if they didn't, we didn't hear them.
But we didn't have any, there weren't any churches on campus at all then.
And

I mean, I think there was two or three years where every Sunday my father would go out and talk to different people to find out what kind of, what they wanted, what denomination they wanted, and they finally got theirs.
But otherwise, they marched them all in on Sunday, you know, they marched the whole corps into the, finally it was to the,
God Hall, but before that it was next door.
It was on the road there with the dormitories.
And there would be a worship service?
There was a worship service and some prominent minister from, it didn't make any what denomination, it was a different one every time, but they had a different one every Sunday.
Did you and your parents go to church during those years?
Yes.
Where did you all worship?
Well, we went in, Brian, to the Presbyterian Church.
We'd drive in on Sunday.
And it was down there by the railroad?
Yeah.
Were your parents Presbyterians before they came?
Yes.
Were there other Presbyterians on the campus?
What other families?
No, there were a lot.
Later on there were the Frank Andersons and the Wilcoxes.
He was the principal and then the superintendent of the school when we got our high school.
There were quite a few.
Let's see.
Back on the campus, the classes were held from Monday morning till Saturday at noon.
But you youngsters went to school just Monday through Friday.
That's right.
And who were some of the teachers in the high school that you remember?
Were there some special people that were really good?
Yes, but they came and went, and not anybody that was here permanently.
So there weren't many of them that were wives of faculty members?
None, really.
In the beginning, I think finally that happened a little bit later on, but they were.
Let's go back to the dances.
How did the people behave at the dances?
They behaved fine.
We had programs and we knew who we would go to dance with and you went to a certain place after the dance and then you got your next person that was on your program.
How did you put the names on your program?
There was a pencil hanging on your dance program.
Okay.
And so they filled out the program that night?
Yeah, that night people would come up and ask if they could have a dance.
And, of course, you were very popular because there weren't many girls there.
All right, so there were girls from the campus.
Were there girls from Bryan?
Oh, always, always.
but not many from the campus because there weren't that many of us at that age group, but always from Bryan.
And then for the big dances, the families on campus took care of the student girls, but they'd come and stay with you.
We always had girls staying with us.
What did the families charge for that?
Oh, no, no.
Normally, what dance would have the largest out-of-town crowd?
I guess maybe the RVs because they came and stayed three days.
Did girls come down from CIA?
Oh, yes, a lot of them from CIA.
Now I've heard about boys writing letters to girls with the same post office box number for a blind date.
That didn't happen way back there?
If it did, I didn't know it.
It probably did, though.
It did.

uh my mind recalls that dr bezell came here as president yes in 1915. yes please share anything you remember about the bezells well uh elaine the daughter was was uh well i think she was in high school and now i see i wasn't but five years old then so uh but but she
We looked up to her, and Dr. Brazil was very highly thought of.
I interviewed her about a year ago, and she was marvelous.
She lives in Oklahoma City.
Was she a pleasant young lady?
Oh, yes.
How often did you and your family go to the president's house in those days?
I don't remember at all.
I mean, I didn't go at all because...
Describe Dr. Bezell physically.
What did he look like?
Well, he was a big, heavy-set man, like most of them were back in those days.
And she said he didn't believe in drinking.
Oh, no, no.
They were Baptists.
That's right.
Very definite Baptists.
And from Navasota.
On drinking, where did the students, if they wanted to get something to drink, where did they get it?
They didn't get it.
They weren't supposed to drink and they didn't get it.
And my father was very opposed to it.
We never had a... We finally... Well, I had something and I almost died in the...
A neighbor across the street brought over a little whiskey and kept me alive until the doctor got there.
After that, we had a little bottle that we kept in the old cedar chest.
But that same little bottle was there for many, many years.
After a dance, if a group of students and their dates wanted to have a big time, where did they go?
Well, they had to go back to a house.
Okay.
Somebody's house because people just don't realize there was nothing.
There was just nothing.
What was there at Northgate or Southgate when you were in high school?
Was there anything?
Well, in high school, what's his name?
I know you know who I'm going to talk about it.
funny little old man, and he had a house up there.
Can't think of what his name was.
He was a bachelor, and he entertained the high school kids, and he was writing an opera.
Writing an opera?
He was writing an opera, yeah.
But he had several pianos, and we'd go.
He'd entertain us, and we'd go up to his house, but
There was just really, there was nothing.
I mean, there was no place to stay.
And the people, look at me in the heart, but when I say that the people used our bathroom, because, you know, there was no place for women to go to the bathroom or anything.
It was just, it was a boys' school.
And we was there close by where they could stop by on the way to the ball game.
Was it acceptable for you as a young girl to walk down the hallway of the A&M buildings?
Or did your family tell you to stay out of those buildings?
Oh, no.
I mean, there wasn't any reason to go.
And when they built a new building, we were always there to serve the punch and to do the things like that.
Let's see.
Describe the Andersons.
Frank.
Yes, ma'am.
Well, they lived behind us.
And Frank Anderson also came from Mississippi, so he and my father had, you know, things in common.
Describe him.
What was he like?
He was a very fine person.
Bigs?
No, he wasn't big.
He wasn't a big man, but he was a good coach.
Now, he was one of the coaches and later would be a part of the commandant.
What about Coach D.X.
Bible?
Describe him.
Well, he was a coach and a good one, and he was at my wedding.
Really?
Yeah, yeah.
He was at my wedding.
Let's see.
Did you by chance know a football player named Heine Weir?
No.
The name I do, but I didn't know him.
I ask because in 1959, I taught at Schreiner College in Kerrville, and he was then the dean.
Oh, no.
Then I later learned that he was the player who had the hurt leg that King Gill would have replaced as the 12th man.
No.
Isn't that interesting?
Did you know King Gill by chance?
No, no.
Okay.
He was older.
Describe Coach Norton's personality, I mean Coach Bible's personality.
You said he was a good coach.
Well, you know, I was just a little girl.
I mean, I don't, the only time that I really came in contact with those people was we had a,
We'd have summer picnics.
Oh, describe those.
And we'd go out to the old fish pot, which is sitting over here someplace now, close to the...
